english:
  title: Record of the Great Canon Hall at Yongmun Temple on Mount Miji in Jiping County
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A complete set of the Great Canon was donated through the generosity of a certain official. Originally placed in the Yongzang Temple of Ganghwa Province to protect it from unforeseen calamity, it suffered greatly when the Japanese raiders began attacking the coastal regions from the year Gyeongyin onward, for Ganghwa lay directly in their path of destruction. The granddaughter of the Gu clan perished, as did the wife of Indang, a commander of a thousand households. The wife of Minister O Jasun conceived a plan, saying: "Our ancestor took refuge in the Buddha's Law and made this donation of the Great Canon, yet through misfortune it was trampled by enemy hands, nearly half lost. How can we not restore what was damaged?" Thus they moved it to Gyeongcheon Temple, catalogued each function, and bound the volumes anew, making the old shine like new again. Yet she reflected further: "This temple too lies near water, scarcely more than a stone's throw from Yongzang. Would not a temple deep within mountain valleys, shrouded in mist, serve better as its sanctuary?"

    Meanwhile, the monks Jicheon and others of Mount Miji were seeking patronage for the Canon throughout the capital. The Gu clan, delighted to hear of this, shared their family's history. Jicheon and his companions rejoiced at obtaining so great a treasure. In this moment, the offering came to fruition without effort, the Canon found its true home, and both giver and receiver transcended the attachment of giving and receiving. What the Yongmun Temple had lacked since its founding was suddenly brought together in a single day. The descendants of the Gu clan, though they extend a hundred generations hence, shall never bear worry for the Great Canon's fate. Moreover, this brings solace to their ancestor's spirit in the unseen realm. The celestial guardians and eight classes of protective beings at Yongmun shall surely protect the Canon as they would guard the very eyes of their own.

    I confess I have never favored the teachings of the Buddha. When I first heard speak of a thousand cases and ten thousand scrolls, I wondered at such abundance. Yet learning their contents—the Sutras, the Vinaya, the Shastras—I came to understand. The Sutras expound the words of Buddha and the Bodhisattvas; the Vinaya clarifies their discipline; the Shastras elaborate their meaning. Not all proceeds from the golden mouth of the Sage himself, yet even those writings that support his Way and touch upon principles of truth were gathered in. Thus the vastness of a thousand cases and ten thousand scrolls finds its justification. Those who study these teachings, reading the texts with their eyes while seeking their meaning with their hearts, pursuing the subtle mysteries that a thousand sages have left untransmitted—finding them between the lines and in the strokes of characters—do not betray their teacher's instruction. But should one say that in a mere finger-snap the Canon is complete, what of those tens of years at Deer Park and the banks of the Baiji River, when heavenly and human beings gathered round the Buddha? What work was being done then?

    Yet know this: the babbling stream is itself the Buddha's broad tongue; the eyelashes before our eyes remain forever unseen. Let those who study the Way take this teaching to heart and neglect it not. The Great Canon Hall consists of three bays, and its construction was aided by the donation of Lady Won of North Won County.

    Written in the eighth month of autumn in the year Muo.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Deer Park (Yongya-won) refers to the Sarnath in central India, where the Buddha first preached to five monks.
  - key: ''
    value: The allusion to 'finger-snap' and 'Deer Park' criticizes those who seek enlightenment through sudden awakening while dismissing the Buddha's actual years of teaching.
  - key: ''
    value: The closing metaphor about 'eyelashes before our eyes' suggests that truth lies closest to us yet remains invisible—a reminder that spiritual cultivation requires direct personal experience.
